{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7e3f1fb6-9d8b-4deb-a53d-9438348aa227","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but I can answer from general .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app so the OS writes a core file on crash.\n\n2. **Check macOS crash reports** — look in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` system-wide). macOS automatically generates `.ips` / `.crash` files for crashed processes.\n\n3. **Use `/cores/`** — macOS writes core dumps to `/cores/core.<pid>`. Ensure the directory exists and is writable:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze the dump** — open it with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **If `/cores/` is empty** — macOS may have SIP restrictions. Check with `sysctl kern.coredump` (should be `1`). On newer macOS, you may need to boot into Recovery Mode to adjust SIP settings for core dumps.\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump` (that's a CoreCLR tool). The OS-level core dump via `ulimit -c unlimited` + `/cores/` is the standard recovery path.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0d5c8e4c-f715-498c-a228-964723f9bcd0","outputTokens":360,"requestId":"D81B:2749A7:61523A6:693904E:69FBF08F"},"id":"d4fdba99-67e8-44cc-a761-241e42767e17","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:53:29.535Z","parentId":"49191f89-04a5-4925-af0b-ada97e0f6fb2"}
